==Contribution to Early Arabic Literature==

Al-Aṣma’ī was among a group of scholars who edited and recited the [[Jahiliyyah|Pre-lslāmic]] and Islāmic poets of the Arab tribes up to the era of the [[Abbasid|Banū al-‘Abbās]]{{refn|group=n|For translations of some of these ancient poems, {{sfn|Mufaḍḍal, Mufaḍḍalīyāt (Lyall) and Tammām, Al-Ḥamāsah.}}}}{{sfn|Dodge|p=344}}

He memorised thousands of verses of rajaz poetry{{sfn|Khallikān|loc=II|p=124}} and edited a substantial portion of the canon of Arab poets, but produced little poetry of his own. {{sfn|Dodge|p=361}}.  He met criticism for neglecting the ‘rare forms’ (nawādir  - {{lang|ar|نوادر}}) and lack of care in his abridgments.{{refn|group=n|note on various translation in Flügel and Beatty MS.{{sfn|Dodge|pp=119-121}}}}

===List of Edited Poets{{refn|group=n|Compare this list with Aṣma’ī, Fuḥālat al-Shu‘arā’.}}===

