*Al-Kumayt ibn Ma‘rūf {{refn|group=n|Poet of a Bedouin family of poets, early period of Islam. {{sfn|Iṣbahānī|loc=pt.XIX|p=109}}{{sfn|Qutaybah|loc=‘Uyūn, I|pp=35, 81}}{{sfn|Qutaybah|loc=‘Uyūn, IV|p= 7}}}}{{sfn|Dodge|p=347}}
*Al-‘Ajjāj al-Rājaz, Abū Shāthā’ ‘Abd Allāh ibn Ru’bah.{{refn|group=n|Poet of al-Baṣrah, master of [[rajaz]] verse. Died early C8th. {{sfn|Khallikān|loc=I|p=527}}{{sfn|Qutaybah|loc=Shi’r|p=374}}}}. For his son, see Ru’bah.{{sfn|Dodge|pp=252, 348}}
*Ru’bah ibn al-‘Ajjāj, called Abū Muḥammad Ru’bah ibn ‘Abd Allāh {{refn|group=n|Authority on rajaz poetry and Arab folklore; lived at al-Baṣrah; died as a fugitive soon after 763. {{sfn|Khallikān|loc=I|p=527}}{{sfn|Durayd|p=159}}{{sfn|Iṣbahānī|loc=pt. XXI|p=84}}{{sfn|Dodge|pp=193, 252, 312, 348, 356}}}}, was a contemporary of al-Aṣma’ī whose poetry al-Aṣma’ī recited.
*Jarīr ibn ‘Aṭīyah{{refn|group=n|His lineage was a branch of the Tamīm Tribe; he was the famous court poet, first with caliph al-[[Al-Hajjaj ibn Yusuf|Ḥajjāj]] in Iraq, after with ‘[[caliph Abd al-Malik |Abd al-Mālik]] (685-705) at Damascus. He died in 728/729. {{sfn|Khallikān|loc=I|p=294}}{{sfn|Iṣbahānī|loc=VII|p=38}}{{sfn|Dodge|pp=125, 209, 235, 289, 348, 349}}}} al-Aṣma’ī was among group of editors who included Abū ‘Amr [al-Shaybānī], and Ibn al-Sikkīt.{{sfn|Dodge|p=348}}{{sfn|Thatcher|loc=Aṣmai,I|p=763|}}{{refn|group=n|For life of Aṣma’ī, see [[Ibn Khallikān]], ''Biographical Dictionary'', translated from the Arabic by [[William McGuckin de Slane|McG. de Slane]] (Paris and London, 1842), vol. ii. pp. 123-127. *For his work as a grammarian, G. Flügel, ''Die grammatischen Schulen der Araber'' (Leipzig, 1862), pp. 72-80.}}

