The '''Asmat Museum of Culture and Progress''' ('''AMCP''') is located in the city of [[Agats]], in the [[Papua province]] of [[Indonesia]]. It was conceived by the Catholic Crosier missionary [[Frank Trenkenschuh]] in 1969 as a way to preserve traditional [[Asmat people|Asmat]] art as well as provide economic outlets to the Asmat people. It was built by the Catholic Crosier Diocese of Agats-Asmat, which also owns the museum, and supported by Crosier Fathers and Brothers Bishop Alphonse Sowada, originally from [[Elmdale, Minnesota]], US.<ref name="Crosier Bishop Sowada and Diocesan Art Museum">{{cite web | url=http://mission.stcdio.org/mission-office-homepage/global-solidarity/global-connections/papua/ | title=The late Bishop Alphonse Sowada: 40 years of missionary service; Crosiers and the Asmat; Asmat Museum: Preservation of a People | publisher=Catholic Diocese of Saint Cloud Mission Office | accessdate=16 July 2015}}</ref><ref name="AMAA@UST">{{cite web | url=http://art.stthomas.edu/asmat/about-the-museum | title=AMAA@UST | publisher=St. Thomas University, St. Paul, MN, US | accessdate=16 July 2015}}</ref>
The American artist [[Tobias Schneebaum]] and Ursula and Gunter Konrad helped in establishing the museum and it officially opened on August 17, 1973.<ref name="Asmat History">{{cite web|url=http://www.holmes.anthropology.museum/asmat/history.html |title=Asmat History |publisher=Lowell D. Holmes Museum of Anthropology, Wichita State University, US |accessdate=16 July 2015 |deadurl=yes |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20150710035831/http://www.holmes.anthropology.museum/asmat/history.html |archivedate=10 July 2015 }}</ref>
The museum has catalogued approximately 1,200 items to its collection.<ref name="SCHN">{{cite book |title=Asmat Images |last=Schneebaum |first=Tobias |publisher=Crosier Mission Press |year=1985 |isbn=0-918728-59-2}}{{Page needed|date=September 2010}}</ref> Over 600 are on display, including over 300 sculptural pieces, ancestor poles, shields, and drums.<ref>{{cite book |title=Asmat: Perception of Life in Art: The Collection of the Asmat Museum of Culture and Progress |publisher=K. Kühlen Verlag GmbH & Co. KG |publicationplace=Mönchengladbach, Germany |editor1=Ursula Konrad |editor2=Alphonse Sowada |editor3=Gunter Konrad |isbn=3-87448-229-4<!--English ISBN cited; German: ISBN 3-87448-227-8; Indonesian editions: ISBN 3-87448-228-6--> |date=2002}}</ref>
Later, upon retiring to his native [[St. Cloud, Minnesota|St. Cloud]], MN, US area, Bishop emeritus Sowada was also instrumental in founding a second Asmat museum, the [[American Museum of Asmat Art]] which opened in 1995 at the [[University of St. Thomas (Minnesota)|University of St. Thomas]] in [[Saint Paul, Minnesota|St. Paul]], [[Minnesota]], where it also appears under the acronyms AMAA and AMAA@UST.<ref name="AMAA@UST"/>
The director of the Asmat Museum of Culture and Progress, as of 2007, has been Eric Sarkol with John Ohoiwirin as assistant.
Building upon a 1968-1974 [[United Nations]] funded Asmat wood carving project, the museum hosts an annual woodcarving competition and auction. The 31st Asmat Culture Festival sponsored by the Museum was scheduled for 8–13 October 2015.<ref name="Asmat History"/><ref name="31st Asmat Culture Festival sponsored by the Museum">{{cite web | url=https://www.facebook.com/359194677580073/photos/a.359210410911833.1073741828.359194677580073/471125063053700/?type=1&theater | title=31st Asmat Culture Festival sponsored by the Museum | publisher=Asmat Museum of Culture and Progress | accessdate=16 July 2015}}</ref>
