[[File:Divadlo v Kotcích.tif|thumb|Divadlo v Kotcích]]

The '''Divadlo v Kotcích''', German '''Theater an der Kotzen''', in English more usually '''Kotzen Theatre''', was a [[Prague]] theatre and opera venue on v Kotcích street, which had its heyday 1739-1783 as the second public opera theatre in Prague.<ref>Contrary to a widespread misconception, the opera theatre of Count Franz Anton von Sporck was not a private theatre, but a public theatre, as documented in [[Daniel E. Freeman]] - ''The opera theater of Count Franz Anton von Sporck in Prague'' - 1992.</ref>  Spoken plays and ballets were also presented there.  

For many seasons it was run by the Italian impresario [[Santo Lapis]], then [[Giovanni Battista Locatelli]], who staged [[Ezio (Gluck)|Gluck's Prague Ezio, 1750]], and other works.<ref>[http://www.ceskyhudebnislovnik.cz/slovnik/index.php?option=com_mdictionary&action=record_detail&id=572 History of performances in Czech]</ref> Later impresarios who worked there include [[Gaetano Molinari]] and [[Giuseppe Bustelli]]. The more correct "Theater an der Kotzen" was often colloquially referred to as the "Kotzentheater," Kotzen being a Slavonic-German term for a market.<ref>''The opera theater of Count Franz Anton von Sporck in Prague'' - Page 72 Daniel E. Freeman - 1992 "Already by 1737 there were firm plans to construct a new permanent theater in the Old City of Prague in the "Kotzen," which at that time meant a market or bazaar.85"</ref> It closed in 1783 for safety reasons.<ref>''Opera v Praze'' Alexandr Buchner - 1985  "It was reconstructed from the old market hall. Its first director was Santo Lapis, impresario of the Italian operatic society. The V Kotcích Theatre was discontinued in 1783 for safety reasons."</ref>

It was preceded by the opera theatre of Count [[Franz Anton von Sporck]], which operated between 1724 and 1735, and succeeded by Count Nostitz's "National Theatre," now the [[Estates Theatre]] (or "Stavovské divadlo"), which opened on 21 April 1783. The current [[National Theatre (Prague)|National Theatre, "Národní divadlo"]] did not open until 1881.

