'''Norman Brosterman''' (born 1952) is an American author, art dealer, and collector. He is an authority on the history of children's [[Construction toy|construction toys]] and [[Building blocks|building blocks]], and antique pattern-making and mosaic toys. He has written ''Inventing Kindergarten'' (1997) on the history of the original [[kindergarten]] system and its influence on the development of [[abstract art]] and [[modern architecture]] in the 20th century.<ref>[https://www.nytimes.com/books/97/09/07/reviews/970907.07elkindt.html "Play's the Thing".] [[David Elkind]], ''[[New York Times]]'', 7 September 1997. Retrieved 5 February 2018.</ref><ref>[http://www.froebelweb.org/web2008.html Inventing Kindergarten.] Johannes Froebel-Parker, Froeebel Web. Retrieved 5 February 2018.</ref><ref>[https://www.publishersweekly.com/978-0-8109-3526-6 Review: ''Inventing Kindergarten''.] publishersweekly.com Retrieved 5 February 2018.</ref> In 1989, his collection of antique construction toys was acquired by the [[Canadian Centre for Architecture]] in Montreal.<ref>[http://inventingkindergarten.com/author Norman Brosterman.] Inventing Kindergarten. Retrieved 5 February 2018.</ref>

